{"title_page": "Thomas Parry (ambassador)", "text_new": "{{short description|English politician and diplomat}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n'''Sir Thomas Parry''' (1541 \u2013 30 May 1616) was an [[English people|English]] politician and diplomat during the [[Tudor period]].<ref name=rbh>[http://www.berkshirehistory.com/bios/tparryjr.html Royal Berkshire History: Sir Thomas Parry Junior (1541-1616)]</ref>\n\nHe was the son of [[Thomas Parry (Comptroller of the Household)|Sir Thomas Parry]] Senior of [[Welford Park]] in [[Berkshire]], the [[Comptroller of the Household|Controller of the Royal Household]], by his wife, Anne, the daughter of Sir William Reade of [[Boarstall]] in [[Buckinghamshire]].<ref name=rbh /> He was educated at [[Winchester School]] (1558).\n\nHe first entered Parliament in 1571 as member for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]]. He was appointed [[High Sheriff of Berkshire]] for 1575\u201376 and 1587\u201388 and made a deputy lieutenant for Berkshire in 1593.\n\nFrom 1586 to 1587, during the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England]], he was the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5V09AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Browne+Willis%22&source=bl&ots=NlR4ZTzW3S&sig=Pm35du8puwXQ6zQe811JbwnjHIc&hl=en&ei=01hsTJKDKpGj4QaR55XZAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CCYQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Browne WIllis ''Notitia parliamentaria, or, An history of the counties, cities, and boroughs in England and Wales: ... The whole extracted from mss. and printed evidences'' 1750]</ref> and for [[St Albans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Albans]] in 1610.<ref name=rbh /> \n\nIn 1601, he was knighted and appointed [[List of ambassadors of the Kingdom of England to France|English ambassador to France]] for four years.<ref name=rbh /> Upon his return to England, he was made [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]].<ref name=rbh /> In 1614 he was again reelected to Parliament for Berkshire but, after being censured for interference in the election at Stockbridge, was dismissed from the House. He also temporarily lost his position as Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster.\n\nHe died intestate in 1616 at his home, [[Hamstead Marshall]] House, and was buried in [[Westminster Abbey]].<ref name=rbh /> He had married Dorothy Brooke of Bristol, maid of honour to the Queen; they had no children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/parry-thomas-1544-1616|publisher= History of Parliament |title=PARRY, Thomas (1544-1616) of Hampstead Marshall, Berks|accessdate = 29 June 2013}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]]\n|before=[[John Hastings (died c. 1585)|John Hastings]]\n|before2= [[Richard Inkpenne]]\n|with= [[George Trenchard (c. 1548\u20131630)|George Trenchard]]\n|years=1571\n|after= [[Miles Sandys (died 1601)|Miles Sandys]]\n|after2=[[John Russell, Lord Russell (died 1584)|John Russell, Lord Russell]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]]\n|before=[[Henry Neville (Gentleman of the Privy Chamber)|Sir Henry Neville]]\n|before2= [[Edward Unton (captain)|Edward Unton]]\n|with= [[Edward Unton (captain)|Edward Unton]]\n|years=1586\u20131587\n|after= [[Henry Norreys (colonel-general)|Sir Henry Norreys]]\n|after2=[[Edward Hoby|Sir Edward Hoby]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Albans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Albans]]\n|before=[[Tobie Matthew]]\n|before2= [[Adolph Carey]]\n|with= [[Henry Helmes|Sir Henry Helmes]]\n|years=1610\u20131614\n|after= [[Thomas Perient]]\n|after2=[[Henry Finch (died 1625)|Henry Finch]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]]\n|before=[[Henry Neville (died 1615)|Sir Henry Neville]]\n|before2= [[Francis Knollys (admiral)|Francis Knollys]]\n|with= [[Henry Neville (died 1615)|Sir Henry Neville]]\n|years=1614\u20131616\n|after= [[Richard Lovelace, 1st Baron Lovelace|Sir Richard Lovelace]]\n|after2=[[Robert Knollys (politician died 1659)|Sir Robert Knollys]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parry, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1541 births]]\n[[Category:1616 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hamstead Marshall]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of England for Berkshire]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1571]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of England to France]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n[[Category:Parry family (England)]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1586\u20131587]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1604\u20131611]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1614]]\n[[Category:17th-century English diplomats]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Berkshire]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|English politician and diplomat}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}}\n{{Use British English|date=December 2016}}\n'''Sir Thomas Parry''' (1541 \u2013 30 May 1616) was an [[English people|English]] politician and diplomat during the [[Tudor period]].<ref name=rbh>[http://www.berkshirehistory.com/bios/tparryjr.html Royal Berkshire History: Sir Thomas Parry Junior (1541-1616)]</ref>\n\nHe was the son of [[Thomas Parry (Comptroller of the Household)|Sir Thomas Parry]] Senior of [[Welford Park]] in [[Berkshire]], the [[Comptroller of the Household|Controller of the Royal Household]], by his wife, Anne, the daughter of Sir William Reade of [[Boarstall]] in [[Buckinghamshire]].<ref name=rbh /> He was educated at [[Winchester School]] (1558).\n\nHe first entered Parliament in 1571 as member for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]]. He was appointed [[High Sheriff of Berkshire]] for 1575\u201376 and 1587\u201388 and made a deputy lieutenant for Berkshire in 1593.\n\nFrom 1586 to 1587, during the reign of [[Elizabeth I of England]], he was the [[Member of Parliament]] for [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=5V09AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover&dq=%22Browne+Willis%22&source=bl&ots=NlR4ZTzW3S&sig=Pm35du8puwXQ6zQe811JbwnjHIc&hl=en&ei=01hsTJKDKpGj4QaR55XZAg&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&resnum=6&ved=0CCYQ6AEwBQ#v=onepage&q&f=false Browne WIllis ''Notitia parliamentaria, or, An history of the counties, cities, and boroughs in England and Wales: ... The whole extracted from mss. and printed evidences'' 1750]</ref> and for [[St Albans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Albans]] in 1610.<ref name=rbh /> \n\nIn 1601, he was knighted and appointed [[List of ambassadors of the Kingdom of England to France|English ambassador to France]] for four years.<ref name=rbh /> Upon his return to England, he was made [[Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster]].<ref name=rbh /> In 1614 he was again reelected to Parliament for Berkshire but, after being censured for interference in the election at Stockbridge, was dismissed from the House. He also temporarily lost his position as Chancellor of the Duchy of Lancaster.\n\nHe died intestate in 1616 at his home, [[Hamstead Marshall]] House, and was buried in [[Westminster Abbey]].<ref name=rbh /> He had married Dorothy Brooke of Bristol, maid of honour to the Queen; they had no children.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n*{{cite web| url=http://www.historyofparliamentonline.org/volume/1558-1603/member/parry-thomas-1544-1616|publisher= History of Parliament |title=PARRY, Thomas (1544-1616) of Hampstead Marshall, Berks|accessdate = 29 June 2013}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|en}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Bridport (UK Parliament constituency)|Bridport]]\n|before=[[John Hastings (died c. 1585)|John Hastings]]\n|before2= [[Richard Inkpenne]]\n|with= [[George Trenchard (c. 1548\u20131630)|George Trenchard]]\n|years=1571\n|after= [[Miles Sandys (died 1601)|Miles Sandys]]\n|after2=[[John Russell, Lord Russell (died 1584)|John Russell, Lord Russell]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]]\n|before=[[Henry Neville (Gentleman of the Privy Chamber)|Sir Henry Neville]]\n|before2= [[Edward Unton (captain)|Edward Unton]]\n|with= [[Edward Unton (captain)|Edward Unton]]\n|years=1586\u20131587\n|after= [[Henry Norreys (colonel-general)|Sir Henry Norreys]]\n|after2=[[Edward Hoby|Sir Edward Hoby]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[St Albans (UK Parliament constituency)|St Albans]]\n|before=[[Tobie Matthew]]\n|before2= [[Adolph Carey]]\n|with= [[Henry Helmes|Sir Henry Helmes]]\n|years=1610\u20131614\n|after= [[Thomas Perient]]\n|after2=[[Henry Finch]]}}\n{{succession box\n|title=[[Member of Parliament]] for [[Berkshire (UK Parliament constituency)|Berkshire]]\n|before=[[Henry Neville (died 1615)|Sir Henry Neville]]\n|before2= [[Francis Knollys (admiral)|Francis Knollys]]\n|with= [[Henry Neville (died 1615)|Sir Henry Neville]]\n|years=1614\u20131616\n|after= [[Richard Lovelace, 1st Baron Lovelace|Sir Richard Lovelace]]\n|after2=[[Robert Knollys (politician died 1659)|Sir Robert Knollys]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Parry, Thomas}}\n[[Category:1541 births]]\n[[Category:1616 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Hamstead Marshall]]\n[[Category:People educated at Winchester College]]\n[[Category:Members of the Parliament of England for Berkshire]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1571]]\n[[Category:Ambassadors of England to France]]\n[[Category:Burials at Westminster Abbey]]\n[[Category:Chancellors of the Duchy of Lancaster]]\n[[Category:Parry family (England)]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1586\u20131587]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1604\u20131611]]\n[[Category:English MPs 1614]]\n[[Category:17th-century English diplomats]]\n[[Category:High Sheriffs of Berkshire]]\n[[Category:Deputy Lieutenants of Berkshire]]\n\n\n{{England-pre1707-MP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Tassedethe", "label": "safe", "comment": "v2.02 - Repaired 1 link to disambiguation page -(You can help)-Henry Finch", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thomas_Parry_(ambassador)"}
{"title_page": "1999\u20132000 Kilmarnock F.C. season", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{Use British English|date=April 2020}}\n{{Infobox football club season\n|club=[[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock]]\n|season=[[1999\u20132000 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000]]\n|manager= [[Bobby Williamson]]\n|chairman=\n|stadium=[[Rugby Park]]\n|league=[[1999\u20132000 Scottish Premier League|SPL]]\n|league result='''Ninth place'''\n|cup1=[[1999\u20132000 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]]\n|cup1 result='''Third round''', lost to [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]\n|cup2=[[1999\u20132000 Scottish League Cup|League Cup]]\n|cup2 result='''Semi-final''', lost to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]]\n|cup3=[[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]]\n|cup3 result='''First round'''\n|league topscorer=[[Christophe Cocard|Cocard]] (8)\n|season topscorer=Cocard (8)\n|highest attendance=15,795 v [[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]], SPL, 16 October 1999 \n|lowest attendance=5,584 v Alloa Athletic, Scottish Cup, 5 February 2000\n|average attendance=9,419 \n|pattern_la1=_whiteshoulders\n|pattern_b1=_whitestripes4\n|pattern_ra1=_whiteshoulders\n|pattern_sh1=_bluesides\n|leftarm1=0000ff\n|body1=0000ff\n|rightarm1=0000ff\n|shorts1=\n|socks1=\n|pattern_la2=_blacklower\n|pattern_b2=_thinblacksides\n|pattern_ra2=_blacklower\n|pattern_sh2=_whitesides\n|pattern_so2=_4_hoops_thin_burgundy\n|leftarm2=660000\n|body2=660000\n|rightarm2=660000\n|shorts2=000000\n|socks2=\n|prevseason=[[1998\u201399 Kilmarnock F.C. season|1998\u201399]]\n|nextseason=[[2000\u201301 Kilmarnock F.C. season|2000\u201301]]\n}}\n\nThe [[1999\u20132000 in Scottish football|1999\u20132000 season]] was [[Kilmarnock F.C.|Kilmarnock's]] second season in the [[1999\u20132000 Scottish Premier League|Scottish Premier League]]. Kilmarnock also competed in the [[1999\u20132000 Scottish Cup|Scottish Cup]], [[1999\u20132000 Scottish League Cup|Scottish League Cup]] and the [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]].\n\n\n\n==Summary==\n\n\n===Season===\nKilmarnock finished ninth in the [[1999\u20132000 Scottish Premier League|Scottish Premier League]] with 37 points. They reached the semi\u2013final of the [[Scottish League Cup|League Cup]], losing to [[Celtic F.C.|Celtic]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.londonhearts.com/scores/a2000/kilmarnock2000.htm | title=Results for Kilmarnock for 1999\u201300 | publisher=londonhearts.com | accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> Kilmarnock also reached the third round of the [[Scottish Cup]], losing to [[Alloa Athletic F.C.|Alloa Athletic]]<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.londonhearts.com/scores/a2000/kilmarnock2000.htm | title=Results for Kilmarnock for 1999\u201300 | publisher=londonhearts.com | accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> and lost in the first round of the [[1999\u20132000 UEFA Cup|UEFA Cup]] to [[1. FC Kaiserslautern|1. FC Kaiserslautern]].<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.worldfootball.net/report/europa-league-1999-2000-1-runde-kilmarnock-fc-1-fc-kaiserslautern/ | title=Kilmarnock 0 2 1. FC Kaiserslautern | publisher=worldfootball.net | accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n\n==Results and fixtures==\n\n''Kilmarnock's score comes first''\n\n{{legend2|#CCFFCC|Win|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#FFFFCC|Draw|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#FFCCCC|Loss|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#CCCCCC|Postponed|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n\n\n===Scottish Premier League===\n{{Main article|1999\u20132000 Scottish Premier League}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:100%; text-align:center\"\n!Match!!Date!!Opponent!!Venue!!Result!!Attendance!!Scorers\n|-style=\"background: #FFCCCC;\"\n|1||31 July 1999||[[Rangers F.C.|Rangers]]||A||1\u20132||48,074||[[Ally Mitchell|Mitchell]] 65'\n|-style=\"background: #CCFFCC;\"\n|2||7 August 1999||[[Aberdeen F.C.|Aberdeen]]||H||2\u20130||8,378||[[Garry Hay|Hay]] 38', 62'\n|-style=\"background: #FFCCCC;\"\n|3||15 August 1999||[[St Johnstone F.C.|St Johnstone]]||A||0\u20132||4,681||\n|-style=\"background: #FFCCCC;\"\n|4||21 August 1999||[